         <abstract id="aspace_06142843b6648895ed03ae21c84ed32b">The papers consist of letters written by Henry B. White to his wife, Dorothy Welch White, during World War II. The correspondence details White's military experiences, covering such topics as his basic training in the United States and subsequent postings in Morocco, Northern Africa, India, and Burma. The letters contain detailed descriptions of military training and camp life, the flora and fauna of Africa and India, and Sikh and Hindu rituals. Also included are four letters from George Morgan Welch to his daughter, Dorothy Welch White, written while he was stationed in the Southwest Pacific area in 1943.</abstract>
